President Donald J. Trump has announced his intent to nominate Eric George Nelson of Texas as Ambassador Extraordinary and Plenipotentiary of the United States of America to Bosnia and Herzegovina. Nelson is a career member of the Senior Foreign Service and has been an American diplomat since 1990. He currently serves as Deputy Executive Secretary and Director of the Executive Office of the Executive Secretariat, Office of the Secretary of State. Nelson has served in various United States missions overseas and began his career as a Peace Corps volunteer in Liberia. He holds a B.S.Ch.E. from Rice University and an M.B.A. from the University of Texas at Austin, and speaks Spanish, German, and Italian.

President Trump also announced his intent to nominate Matthew John Matthews of Virginia as Ambassador Extraordinary and Plenipotentiary of the United States of America to Brunei Darussalam. Matthews is a career member of the Senior Foreign Service and has been an American diplomat since 1986. He currently serves as Ambassador for Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation and Deputy Assistant Secretary for Australia, New Zealand, and the Pacific Islands. Matthews has had senior assignments in various countries in the Asia-Pacific region, including Australia, Malaysia, Hong Kong, China, and the Department of Defense Pacific Command. He holds a B.A. from the University of Oregon and an M.A. from Johns Hopkins University, and is fluent in Mandarin Chinese.